problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/reverse-linked-list-ii/description/
Intuition
When i looked this problem i realized it is a question based on inplace linked list reversal pattern , but the main problem was i have to replace something between the linked list not the entire linked list , now to do that firstly i need to reach to the point or node just before i have to do the reversal which would be left - 1 , now there can be a scenario i have to start reversal from first node , in that case i will not have any node before the left so for safety , i take a dummy node with val 0 and next as head , now i assign a pointer prev which is going to point to the point before the left node , another key problem in this question is that how many nodes i have to reverse , for that its simple we do it right - left + 1 time , the third part is we have to merge the node before left to reversed lift head and reversed list tail to the node after right .

Approach
so the approach is prev points at dummy initally , we then move prev left - 1 times so that it reaches the node before left , now we safely store the left in a ponter variable , leftnode = prev.next , now we also take one variable curr that also points at prev.next , after that we disconnect prev from the list , now we start reversing the nodes right - left + 1 time, after that our list is divided into 3 parts , the part before the left , the reversed part and the part after the right , now we connect the head of reversed list prev to the node before left , prev.next = helper , and connect the tail of head to the part after the right , leftnode.next = curr , then we return dummy.next as head of the new list

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Space complexity:
O(1)
Code
# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.next = next
class Solution:
    def reverseBetween(self, head: Optional[ListNode], left: int, right: int) -> Optional[ListNode]:
        dummy = ListNode(0,head)
        prev = dummy
        
        for _ in range(left-1):
            prev = prev.next
        leftnode = prev.next
        
        curr = prev.next
        helper = None
        for _ in range(right - left + 1):
            newnode = curr.next
            curr.next = helper
            helper = curr
            curr = newnode
        prev.next = helper
        leftnode.next = curr
        return dummy.next
